Lektionen, die heute aus der Kuba-Krise gelernt werden können
„Thirteen Days” („Dreizehn Tage“), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, is set to premiere in cinemas across numerous countries soon.
Everyone should watch this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events – particularly regarding the controversies surrounding a U.S. national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy convened his closest advisors at the White House.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a site for the deployment of nuclear weapons on Cuba.
The decisions made during the following thirteen days, as well as the decisions that could not be reached, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened during these days in the White House.
Audio recordings made during President Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard initiated a discussion round that was meant to examine the film and the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this round included: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a Harvard history professor who wrote a book on the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a Harvard political science professor who thirty years ago presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision".
Additionally, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was present.
Although the cinematic treatment of the topic was criticized in several points, the discussion participants agreed that the film accurately portrays the problems and pressures that President Kennedy faced, as they actually were.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Missile Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in the case of a crisis, yet it is exclusively the President who ultimately bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – civilian as well as military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be shown, which were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how the enemy thinks; in addition, the communication channels must remain open.
Pressing an enemy into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open, which allow an understanding of the enemy's situation, could turn out to be disastrous.
· The United States is dependent on allies.
Kennedy acted this way because the NATO, other allies, and the opinion of the world had supported him.
· A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into taking action.
The fact that a week passed during which all involved factors were examined and weighed precisely was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a timeframe for deliberation still exist today in view of the currently existing mass media?
Robert McNamara has emphasized that it was necessary to put oneself in the opponent's position.
In one of the much-criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade Kennedy had imposed on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intent, and not as a means to stop specific Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more calmly?
After all, the US had also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station rockets on Cuba merely reflected this policy.
Yet Kennedy showed fear regarding the consequences that a stationing of Soviet missiles in Cuba would have had with respect to Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
"The Berlin crisis was solved by the results of the Cuban crisis," claimed the historian Ernest May.
"It will soon be too late," was a widely circulated argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba, even while the missiles – as they assumed – were en route to Cuba by sea.
An 180,000-man strong US force was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a lightning bombardment that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "I needed thirty years," said McNamara, "to find out that there were already nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and of those 90 were strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about this?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew about it."
And I explicitly recommended that atomic weapons be used.
I knew this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba."
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were ready to let Cuba burn to ashes, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!"
Therefore, an invasion might have resulted in the death of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy government lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often happens when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion would "certainly" have led to a Soviet atomic attack on the USA.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military on Cuba was indeed limited: aircraft of the U-2 type, flying over Cuban airspace, were shot at despite the chairman's explicit instructions to the contrary.
A difficult question that arose during this debate at Harvard, however, is the following: What would have happened if the adversary had not been Khrushchev, who during the crisis was more distinguished by rational behavior, but instead someone of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could one day become reality.
Today's discussions about a limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrible, yet entirely realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new website on the Internet, where essential documents about the Cuban Missile Crisis as well as current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
